<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you buy some stocks that go up and some sto=
cks that go down, then it is usually tax-efficient for you to sell the stoc=
ks that went down (giving you taxable losses that you can use to shield oth=
er income from taxes) and keep the stocks that went up (deferring taxable i=
ncome until you really need the money). I do not give tax advice around her=
e, but this is a popular approach. If you have a bunch of stocks with losse=
s and you sell them, then you will have a lot of cash. If you don=E2=80=99t=
 need the cash (perhaps because you saved so much money on taxes?), you wil=
l probably want to invest it somewhere. You will look around for good inves=
tments, and you might want to buy some stocks that have sold off and are no=
w trading at attractive prices.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Be careful! Some of the beaten-down stocks tha=
t are now trading at attractive prices might be=C2=A0<em>the ones you just =
sold</em>, and that=E2=80=99s bad. In US tax law, you can=E2=80=99t (1) sel=
l stock that went down, (2) claim a taxable loss and (3) immediately go buy=
 that stock again. That=E2=80=99s cheating; that=E2=80=99s the same thing a=
s just=C2=A0<em>holding=C2=A0</em>the stock, and you can=E2=80=99t claim a =
tax loss for just <em>holding=C2=A0</em>the stock. If you do this trade =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0sell a stock, claim a loss, buy it right back =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
at=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30506=
312.264446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaW52ZXN0b3IuZ292L2ludHJvZHVjdGlvbi1pbnZlc3Rpbmcv=
aW52ZXN0aW5nLWJhc2ljcy9nbG9zc2FyeS93YXNoLXNhbGVz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb=
116b599" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> called a =E2=80=9Cwash sale=E2=80=9D</a> and not allowed.=
 (Again, not tax or legal advice.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand if you have some beaten-down=
 stocks, you sell them, you claim a taxable loss, and then you reinvest the=
 money in a=C2=A0<em>different=C2=A0</em>list of beaten-down stocks, that=
=E2=80=99s probably fine. (Not tax advice!) Any two lists of beaten-down st=
ocks will probably have <em>some </em>similarities to=C2=A0each other; ther=
e will be some correlations. If a bunch of tech stocks go down and you sell=
 Meta and buy Alphabet, you will get a taxable loss, but you will keep a so=
mewhat similar exposure.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30506312.264446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvcHVibGljYS5vcmcvYX=
J0aWNsZS9pcnMtZmlsZXMtdGF4ZXMtd2FzaC1zYWxlcy1nb2xkbWFuLXNhY2hz/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB1bac124b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">ProPublica investigation</a> into this sort =
of tax-loss harvesting that begins with a story about selling and buying th=
e=C2=A0<em>most similar possible=C2=A0</em>stocks that are still technicall=
y distinct:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At first glance, July 24, 2015, seems to have =
been a brutal trading day for Steve Ballmer, the former Microsoft CEO. He d=
umped hundreds of stocks, losing at least $28 million.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this was no panicked sell-off. Among the s=
tocks Ballmer sold were those of the Australian mining company BHP and the =
global oil giant Shell. Had Ballmer lost confidence in BHP=E2=80=99s manage=
ment? Was he betting that the price of oil would not soon recover? Not at a=
ll. That very day, Ballmer also bought thousands of shares in BHP and Shell=
. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both Shell and BHP offered two different versi=
ons of their common stock. For each company, the two stocks were legally di=
stinct, but they performed very similarly because, after all, they were sha=
res in the same company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ballmer=E2=80=99s not-so-bad day, in fact, was=
 carefully planned, part of a strategy by Goldman Sachs, which conducted th=
e trades on Ballmer=E2=80=99s behalf, to wield the stock market=E2=80=99s n=
atural volatility to the billionaire=E2=80=99s advantage. At Goldman, the h=
undreds of stocks in Ballmer=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CTax Advantaged Loss Harvest=
ing=E2=80=9D accounts were selected to follow the movement of the broader m=
arkets. Over time, the markets, as they had historically, would buoy Ballme=
r=E2=80=99s investments upward. When, inevitably, some of the stocks underp=
erformed or the whole market dipped, Goldman was ready to pounce, selling o=
ff the losers and replacing them with equivalents.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes, the replacements were nearly identi=
cal securities, as with Shell and BHP. More often, they were not. But well-=
tuned software could easily find the right stocks to keep the accounts trac=
king the market. His losses secured, Ballmer was ready to catch the bounce =
back.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Technically <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30506312.264446/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaXJzLmdvdi9wdWIvaXJz=
LXBkZi9wNTUwLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaf100aaf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the wash sal=
e rules</a> prohibit buying and selling =E2=80=9Csubstantially identical se=
curities,=E2=80=9D but=C2=A0according to ProPublica, in practice, the only =
thing that anyone counts as a =E2=80=9Cwash sale=E2=80=9D is selling and bu=
ying the same CUSIP =E2=80=94=C2=A0the same exact stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0with=
in a 60-day period. Buying and selling different but correlated stocks is f=
ine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some level, this is all standard stuff that=
 is available to retail investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0here is a list of =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30506312.264446=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucm9ib2Fkdmlzb3Jwcm9zLmNvbS93aGljaC1yb2JvLWFkdmlzb3JzLW9mZm=
VyLXRheC1sb3NzLWhhcnZlc3Rpbmcv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1c998024" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
Which Robo-Advisors Offer Tax-Loss Harvesting?</a>,=E2=80=9D and the answer=
 is kind of =E2=80=9Call of them=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I guess it is =
a little funny to sell and buy two classes of the same company=E2=80=99s st=
ock for tax-loss harvesting. Also very funny is that ProPublica called Gold=
man about this, and Goldman was like =E2=80=9Cfine we will stop doing that =
one specific thing=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After inquiries by ProPublica, Goldman said it=
 would halt transactions like Ballmer=E2=80=99s Shell and BHP trades. Goldm=
an conducted a review, according to a statement by the bank, and found that=
 a =E2=80=9Cvery small percentage=E2=80=9D of its =E2=80=9Ctax investment s=
olutions=E2=80=9D trades were =E2=80=9Cinadvertently made in a manner incon=
sistent with our strategy.=E2=80=9D The bank said it strives =E2=80=9Cto pr=
ovide best-in-class investment advice to clients, consistent with both the =
letter and the spirit of all applicable tax laws and regulations.=E2=80=9D =
...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, by Goldman=E2=80=99s own description, it =
is halting only a narrow slice of its loss-generating trades =E2=80=94 the =
ones involving two kinds of stock from the same company. The bank will cont=
inue its broader practice of finding similar stocks that achieve the same e=
ffect.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It would be irresponsible not to!=C2=A0</p>
